Mr Atwoli challenged the National Treasury to get creative and advise the Executive on alternative measures it can employ to sustain the economy.
“The Treasury must learn how to balance between providing services using the taxes and burdening the public in the collection process,” he said.
Many struggling
Mr Atwoli was reacting to the revelation that the government has hit salaried workers with hidden tax increases by revising tax bands, a move which will see those earning above Sh32,333 pay a maximum of 30 per cent in taxes.





He said Cotu is “totally opposed” to the decision and reminded the government that many Kenyan workers, like others globally, are struggling to put food on the table.
In the law enacted last week, Parliament also ended tax reliefs effected as a cushion against the effects of the pandemic.
Regarding this, the Cotu boss said reasons for which the incentives were given remain valid, and warned the government against provoking the public through punitive tax measures.
“By reversing these measures, are we saying we have conquered the pandemic? What has changed since April to convince the government that Kenyans are out of the woods and that these tax measures won’t be burdensome? What are the indicators the government is using?”



