Before the pandemic, the 30 per cent maximum tax rate was being charged on amounts above Sh74,000. The change to Sh32,333 will bring nearly half the population into the bracket.
“Unnecessary" projects
Mr Atwoli further said anybody earning below Sh100,000 must be cushioned.
“Those earning up to Sh100,000 and are on the verge of retirement need to be cushioned further by not being taxed.”
He further said the government must stop spending huge amounts of money on "unnecessary" projects that have no immediate benefit to the public.
“You cannot kill Kenyans while telling them you are building roads for them, because they need to be alive to use the roads. The government must, especially now, learn how to be less ambitious with some of its development projects.”
The umbrella trade union further asked the Kenya Revenue Authority (KRA) to embark on proactive collection of taxes from Kenyans who have mastered the art of evading payment, saying it is “immoral” to overtax a population already hurting due to the pandemic.
“KRA should stop using Covid-19 as a scapegoat because this is not the first time it has missed its revenue collection target. It should innovate and increase their efficiency.” The National Treasury has revised the tax bands for salaried workers. In New Year messages, leaders express high hopes for the future even though it may look bleak. Education CS George Magoha says government will provide three million needy learners with masks. In most schools, lack of classrooms, desks, water, toilets, and dormitories is a stark reality. A new twist in the battle between DP Ruto and his political foe Gideon Moi, for control of vote-rich Rift Valley.